Here's how to implement this in .NET MAUI Shell:

**1. Override back navigation + confirmation dialog:**

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Fire-and-forget since override is synchronous
            Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
            {
                bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                    "Unsaved Changes",
                    "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                    "Discard", "Stay");

                if (leave)
                    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            });

            return true; // Cancel the default navigation
        }

        return false; // Allow normal back navigation
    }
}
```

**2. Custom "Cancel" back button in XAML:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/clr-namespace:YourNamespace"
             x:Class="YourNamespace.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{x:Static local:EditProductPage.CancelBackBehavior}">

    <!-- Or define inline: -->
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior Command="{Binding CancelCommand}"
                           TextOverride="Cancel"
                           IconOverride="" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

**3. ViewModel command handling the cancel tap:**

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave) return;
    }

    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**

- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles the Android hardware/software back button and Shell's default back arrow.
- Setting `BackButtonBehavior` with a `Command` **replaces** the default back behavior entirely — Shell won't navigate back automatically, so you control it fully.
- `TextOverride="Cancel"` changes the label; set `IconOverride=""` (empty) to hide the arrow on iOS.
- Both paths should be implemented together since `OnBackButtonPressed` doesn't fire when `BackButtonBehavior.Command` is set.
